bug.short_desc: [Import/Export] Incomplete validation when importing from directory

long_desc.thetext:
The following instance methods of CheckboxTreeViewer class don't fire any CheckStateChangedEvent.
Affected methods:
setAllChecked(...) setCheckedElements(...) setChecked(...)
Steps to reproduce the bug:
1. File -> Import... 2. File System -> Next 3. Choose a "From directory" using the Browse... button 4. Check the root element from the left pane (the error message saying that "There are no resources currently selected for import." should disappear) 5. Press the Deselect All button and see that no error message is displayed at all!! 6. Recheck the root element twice and the error message is displayed again!!
Solution:
Add fireCheckStateChanged calls inside affected methods

This is a classic case of underspecification - the Javadoc does not explain exactly when events are fired. Since there are many existing clients of CheckboxTreeViewer who may rely on the current implementation, I prefer to clarify the API to say that the setters don't generate any events. After that, this becomes a bug in the Import wizard.

While I agree that changing the current behaviour may break for existing users of CheckboxTreeViewer (eg. eternal loops with two mutually notifying widgets), I believe that this should be fixed in CheckboxTreeViewer.
The reason is that the current behaviour allows two ways of setting a checkmark (manually clicking with the mouse, and calling #setChecked() ), where one has effects for other users of the tree viewer, and one doesn't.
Ie. the visual effects are the same, but the end results aren't.
This just happened to me when I attempted to set check marks in a tree viewer by selecting objects in a GEF viewer. It seemed to work at first... but it didn't really. Which is why I debugged to see what happens, and why I'm reading this bug report.
Of course, one can always subclass, which is what I'll do for now.

Comment to my previous comment:
On closer thought, it would probably be wrong to introduce potential eternal loops (or stack overflows) to fix this bug... probably...?
I'm not sure what the right answer is.

Fixed the underspecification problem by adding the following sentence to the Javadoc where appropriate: "Does not fire events to check state listeners."

bug.short_desc: Unable to associate importe project with CVS

long_desc.thetext:
After installing 3.2, I created a new workspace, then imported some projects from my 3.1 workspace. I used the new Copy Projects Into Workspace option to make a copy of the files.
At the time of the import, I had *NOT* defined the cvs repository location. After the import, the project CVS folders has been copied, but the project is not associated with CVS.
I noticed that the files revision information was not displayed in the navigator view, and suspected that the repository had not been imported along with the project, so I created the repository location in my 3.2 workspace.
At this point, there seems to be no way to associate the project with the repository. The TEAM menu does not contain any options to update the files.
This seems to be an outage in the import process. There should be a warning dialog or something to warn that the repository has not been defined, or, the import should import the repository settings, or there should be a way to subsequently connect the project to the repository after it is created.

Michael, you should be able to reconnect your projects by following these steps:
1) Import your 3.1 projects using the General>Existing Projects into Workspace option from the Import wizard
2) Select your project and check off "Copy projects into workspace"
3) Right click on your imported project and select Team>Share Project...
4) Since your project already has CVS info, you will get a dialog popping up letting you know that it will try to reconnect using the existing repo info -> click Finish. (You will have to enter your username and password again for the repo you are connecting to).
5) Your project will now be connected again to the initial repository.
Please reopen this if you are still having problems. Thanks!

Hi...
Thanks for your patch. I reviewed the patch and have a few questions. When copying the data as columns, why did you organize the data into just two columns? (i.e an address column and a data column). The amount of data to be put in one row is based on the column size of the rendering.
So for a rendering shown like this: &&i : 0x2DA0C8A1 <Hex> Address 0 - 3 4 - 7 8 - B C - F 2DA0C8A0 5C9C2195 449C18E2 057FE3F8 64C7D4EF 2DA0C8B0 1EF7D129 1F8D87B9 E815F6BA DE06D569 2DA0C8C0 1547A132 A2D61899 20A9E5D4 2968104F
The Copy to Column action copies the data into the clipboard like this: &&i : 0x2DA0C8A1 <Hex> 2da0c8a0 5C9C2195 2da0c8a4 449C18E2 2da0c8a8 057FE3F8 2da0c8ac 64C7D4EF : :
My concern here is that this is not the behavior I would expect from a copy action.
Do you have requirement to copy the data into a "flat" list based on the current column size of the rendering?
My second concern is the introduction of a new API (#isShowAddressColumn) in AbstractTableRendering and also in the provisional API AbstractAsyncTableRendering. We have a WSDL defined as follows:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?> <wsdl:definitions xmlns:bons1="http://XmlTest4Library" xmlns:tns="http://XmlTest4Library/inputIF" xmlns:wsdl="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/wsdl/" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" name="inputIF" targetNamespace="http://XmlTest4Library/inputIF"> <wsdl:types> <xsd:schema targetNamespace="http://XmlTest4Library/inputIF" xmlns:bons1="http://XmlTest4Library" xmlns:tns="http://XmlTest4Library/inputIF" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema"> <xsd:import namespace="http://XmlTest4Library" schemaLocation="xsd-includes/http.XmlTest4Library.xsd"/> <xsd:element name="operation1"> <xsd:complexType> <xsd:sequence> <xsd:element name="input1" nillable="true" type="bons1:boin"/> </xsd:sequence> </xsd:complexType> </xsd:element> </xsd:schema> </wsdl:types> <wsdl:message name="operation1RequestMsg"> <wsdl:part element="tns:operation1" name="operation1Parameters"/> </wsdl:message> <wsdl:portType name="inputIF"> <wsdl:operation name="operation1"> <wsdl:input message="tns:operation1RequestMsg" name="operation1Request"/> </wsdl:operation> </wsdl:portType> </wsdl:definitions>
XSD:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?> <xsd:schema xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" targetNamespace="http://XmlTest4Library"> <xsd:complexType name="boin"> <xsd:sequence> <xsd:element minOccurs="0" name="attribute1" type="xsd:string"/> <xsd:element minOccurs="1" name="required2" type="xsd:string"/> <xsd:element minOccurs="0" name="attribute3" type="xsd:string"/> </xsd:sequence> </xsd:complexType> </xsd:schema>
The input gets serialized as such:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?> <xml:bout xmlns:xml="http://XmlTest4Library"> <attribute1>some</attribute1> <attribute2>more</attribute2> <required>entry</required> </xml:bout>
The prefix "xml" is somehow created from the namespace, this causes problems since it's reserved.

Is there any length limitation to ns perfix? According to XMLSchemaToEcoreMapping.pdf 1.2 Schema with targetNamespace
If targetNamespace="http://XmlTest4Library", tne nsPerfix should be 'xmltest4library', not 'xml'

No, there's no length limit. The document describes how the target namespace is turned into a qualified package name where http://XmlTest4Library" becomes library.test4.xml. Only the final segment is used as the nsPrefix. In any case, the document is not a specification; it needs to describe what the code actually does, and if it doesn't, that's an issue with the documentation.
Nick, Can you confirm the exact fixpack version of 2.0.2 this fix is available in ?

The problem is fixed in the head of the maintenance stream, which currently is driving to produce version 2.2.1. You can see what's in any releases from the release notes. http://www.eclipse.org/emf/news/release-notes.php. In older releases, the problem can be worked around with an ecore:nsPrefix annotation on the xsd:schema element, see http://www.eclipse.org/emf/docs/overviews/XMLSchemaToEcoreMapping.pdf. Since there are trivial workarounds, no fix will be provided in older releases.

bug.short_desc: [CommonNavigator][Resource+Java] Refactor actions should be overrideable

long_desc.thetext: In a project, create an HTML page (or a JSF page or a JSP page). In the project navigator, right mouse click on the HTML page. Try to rename it. There is no obvious menu item for renaming it. There is a menu item "Refactor" and if you think to open it, there's a rename under it. HTML pages are not refactored. Nor are images, Javascript libraries, CSS stylesheets, etc. Only Java code is refactored. There should be no "refactor" for something that isn't Java. The Rename menu item should not be buried under a menu head that doesn't make sense.
This will not be addressed for 1.5.1.
Deferring to 2.0.

I have renamed the title from "Java refactor actions should be used for java actions only" to "Refactor actions should be overrideable". After discussions with the originator of the defect, we have identified the following issue and a comprimise to solve the problem:
With the fixes from bug 150674, nested action providers may be overridden and contributed with priorities taken into account.
Now, the only thing that is required is for the Java and Resource extensions to break up their Refactor and Edit action contributions:
+ Refactor the Resource Refactor Action Provider to contribute the same function in the form of a EditActionProvider and a RefactorActionProvider. The former will contribute Copy/Paste/Delete and the second Move/Rename.
+ Refactor the Edit and "Refactor" actions from the JDT PackageExplorerActionProvider into an EditActionProvider and RefactorActionProvider that override the respective Resource Action Providers.
Now, clients (including DTP and products) can choose to override just the Refactor submenu.
This change does not materially change the behavior or function. It is just repackaging it into neater packages for client consumption.
I feel that with the demand from DTP and other commercial products for this functionality, it is imperative that it be released for 3.2.1.
I will attach the relevant patch to this defect. This change must be made at the Resource and JDT level for the scheme to work correctly.

Created an attachment (id=46774) Patches o.e.jdt.ui, o.e.ui.navigator.resources, o.e.ui.tests.navigator

org.eclipse.jdt.ui org.eclipse.ui.navigator org.eclipse.ui.navigator.resources org.eclipse.ui.tests.navigator

Right-click on a Project and/or a regular Folder. The Java Copy/Paste/Delete and Refactor menu actions will be available.
Right-click on a regular JDT element (Package, Source Folder, Java Type), the Java CPD+R actions are available.
Right-click on a plain IFile (e.g. .project), the "CN Test Menu" should replace the JDT Refactor submenu. The Java CPD actions should still be available.
Right-click on a Java Source Folder and an IFile. Only CPD should be available neither the Java Refactor submenu nor the Test "CN Test Menu" is available for this kind of selection.
Turn off the Java extension.
Now, the CN Test Menu will override the Resource Extension's Move+Rename.
Right-click on a project or folder. The Resource Copy/Paste/Delete + Move/Rename should appear.
Right-click on a file. The Resource Copy/Paste/Delete and the Test "CN Test Menu" should appear.
Right-click on a Folder and a File, the Resource CPD should appear along with the Resource Move+Rename. The "CN Test Menu" is not enabled on this type of selection, but the Resource actions are, so they take over the menu.
This should satisfy the requirements from DTP (Brian F.) and IBM (Dusko M.).

Patch makes sense and adds flexibility when contributing actions. Let me know if you want me to release it.
John, what exactly do you mean by 'HTML is not refactored'. Not yet implemented? I would expect that renaming a HTML file also updates all references in other files to it and that's what we call refactoring.

Note that the implementation of the 'Rename' action provided in the JDT refactor menu is doing more than the standard 'Rename' from core resources.
Even if invoked on a resource, Refactor -> Rename notifies registered rename participants (ltk.core.refactoring). I'm not sure if there are clients that listen on HTML or GIF or CSS file renames, but if there were, you really can call this a Refactor > Rename.
So when you replace the refactor menu, better use the JDT Rename and Move actions again to not loose functionality. We might look at this again in 3.3 and maybe move the ResourceRenameAction down to ltk.core.refactoring and try to convince platform.ui to also use rename and move actions that notifies participants.

We have users of our IBM product who are confused because they think "refactoring" is a term specific to code and in this case, java. So, they would not think to look for a refactoring menu on things like html files when they want to rename the files.

In most cases, the Project Explorer seeks to mimic the usability patterns of the Package Explorer, as many users will expect this. As the Package Explorer and Project Explorer do the same thing in this scenario, I'm not convinced that we will have widespread confusion among consumers looking for a "Rename" action.
With the changes for this defect, extenders have the flexibility to customize the menu for their specific users. This is as far as I think we should go for 3.2.1.
In general, having a different menu for _everything_ based on types makes it harder to anticipate where an action is. If users really are confused by the Refactor> submenu approach used by the JDT, there are drop down menus under File to accomplish the same thing.
The intent of these changes is to allow a CNF extension to provide their own actions for cases where integration with JDT Refactor Participants does not make sense (e.g., clients that must exist in JDT and non-JDT configured environments). It is possible to restructure the menu, but my official recommendation on this is for clients taking advantage of this capability to contribute their own Refactor> submenu when overriding the JDT Refactor Action Provider.
Beyond the restructuring of the JDT Action Provider, no material changes will be made to the JDT extension for 1.5.1; particularly not to change how JDT displays the menu.

This approach will do enough to let us fix our problems with refactoring in 3.2.1 timeframe.

The generally useful things that JDT refactoring does and that are not JDT specific should be moved to the platform. Prime example of that would be support for participants.
Please remember that Project Explorer is not replacement only for Package Explorer but also a lot of other navigational views. Stuff common for everybody should be in platform and components should override it only for their specific needs.

They should rather get the actions that the Resource navigator has. But, let them at least use a move/copy and delete actions that informs participants. Over time, plugins tend to accumulate dead code - classes, methods, and fields that are no longer used. Dead code has maintenance cost and adds to the download and install size of Eclipse, so it's worth finding and deleting such code where appropriate. The org.eclipse.core.tools plugin has a utility for locating unused methods and fields, and Martin Aeschlimann from JDT recently provided a patch to remove false matches and present results in the Search view. To use the tool:

http://www.eclipse.org/eclipse/platform-core/downloads.php
2) Install the new plugins in a product extension (only org.eclipse.core.tools is actually needed for this utility). Or, add to an existing install and restart with -clean.
3) Startup with a workspace that contains all projects that are likely to reference the code in question (test suites, fragments, friend plugins, etc)
4) Select one or more Java projects, packages, or types in the Package Explorer, and invoke "Find Unreferenced Members" from the context menu. For most Eclipse projects, selecting all non-API packages is a good start, although it is possible for API packages to contain unused package-private members, or protected members in final classes that can be deleted.
5) Browse the results in the Search view. The results can be sorted by name or path. Keep in mind that classes instantiated through reflection, such as executable extensions, may appear to be unreferenced even though they are used.

bug.short_desc: Improve BufferedRandomInputStream # seek() functionality

long_desc.thetext:
Analysis of the file monitor output done in the bug 150516 suggests that improving BufferedRandomInputStream.seek() method might significantly reduce the number of file reads required.
Consider the following picture: Element 1 occupies bytes 1 to 100. Element 2 occupies bytes 101 to 200. and so on
Let's say the registry reads Element 1. It translates into reading 2048 bytes from disk into the buffer.
Next, registry gets information on the Element 2. To do this, BufferedRandomInputStream.seek() is called to reposition file location to the Element 2 and the read buffer is discarded.
However, the information for the Element 2 was already in the buffer and, in reality, no extra read was necessary.

bug.short_desc: Prune null variable warning by exception path

long_desc.thetext: NumberFormatException is an unchecked exception (since it extends RuntimeException). Accordingly, there is no clue here that the call to the LineNumberReader constructor or the FileReader constructor will not throw one. We must thus consider that the execution may enter the catch block before the second assignment to in, with in being null. I am afraid that we cannot do better for unchecked exceptions. The analysis leverages checked exceptions to clear warnings in comparable situations (aka when the same code pattern catches a checked exception, and none of the constructors throws that said exception).

Understood, appreciate the analysis.
I wasn't sure if it was possible to do a complete analysis and prove that NFE was never thrown by the constructor, or any code referenced by the constructor, but but that might be too expensive.

Yes, I gave it a thought too... But this has challenges of its own, beyond the performance issues, starting with the fact that then you have to put the final system under the analysis process, which is something you would try to avoid, even if you had the opportunity to do so, which is not the most general case by far (here, you would need to certify, so to speak, each JRE before deploying - and except if your company/workgroup/organization is very strong at controlling end user configurations, you would have little control over which JREs get deployed anyway). This would clearly break modularity benefits. I can imagine that some specialized test tools would want to attempt this kind of analysis (get a 'ready to be deployed' system and run extensive static analysis that leverage the hypothesis that the system will go unchanged in production), but this is out of scope for us as long as we assume that the deployed libraries will only honor the APIs known at build time.

bug.short_desc: Refactor externalized strings: provide canonical places where to find them

long_desc.thetext:
Currently externalized strings are defined in many different place using many different ways. They are also redundant, i.e. the same string are defined in many different places. For example, org.eclipse.epf.library\layout\xsl\resources.properties is a reources file. It defines the Artifact string. The same string is also defined in the org.eclipse.epf.uma.edit\plugin.properties plug-in properties file.
We should provide canonical names for external strings (i.e. resource files only in well-defined places). If strings are redundant then it should be unambiguously clear that the they are used for different functions or places in the tool. I recommend naming the resources file appropriately. For example, the Artifact string for the tool UI can be redundantly defined to the Artifact string for the published site, but this should be clear in the resource file name (e.g. uma.properties, ui.properties, publishing.properties) and/or clearly documented in the resource files. The resources file should also be all in the same folder location (i.e. all on the top-level of a plug-in or always in the same subfolder).

This seems to imply gtk_print_settings_get_resolution(settings) has been fixed, but the method OS.gtk_page_setup_get_paper_width (pageSetup, OS.GTK_UNIT_PIXEL) still returns a bogus value (actually points).
Looks like possible hack may now be available to use OS.gtk_page_setup_get_paper_width (pageSetup, OS.GTK_UNIT_INCH) * OS.gtk_print_settings_get_resolution(settings) to get the true page size in pixels and

bug.short_desc: [CheatSheet] Executing multiple commands / actions per item

long_desc.thetext:
Ideally, a good modularized cheat sheet step should contain one command / action (executable) but I found lots of cases in my work which contradict this statement. I believe cheat sheets should be able to perform multiple executables:
1) all at once automatically, to get rid of repetitive work 2) silently, to hide the necessary but meaningless-to-end user kind of work
An example usage for 1) may be the following. Using the existing structure, this can be done using 3 steps, which I believe is a very fine grain and tedious work for end users, unless the cheat sheet is about opening views.
(views below are just random)
<item title="Open Views"> <command serialization = "org.eclipse.ui.views.showView(org.eclipse.ui.views.showView.viewId=org.eclipse.pde.runtime.LogView)" autorun = "true"/> <command serialization = "org.eclipse.ui.views.showView(org.eclipse.ui.views.showView.viewId=org.eclipse.ui.navigator.ProjectExplorer)" autorun = "true"/> <command serialization = "org.eclipse.ui.views.showView(org.eclipse.ui.views.showView.viewId=org.eclipse.search.SearchResultView)" autorun = "true"/> <description> You should now see three newly open views </description> </item>
My actual use case deals more with 2) and lacking this feature really gets annoying from the users point of view or forces me to code other parts of my project in an unmodularized fashion (combining unrelated stuff under one command.)
To be able to implement what I suggest, I introduced a boolean attribute named autorun (default = false) for commands and actions. Executables with autorun = true are kept in a list and executed whenever the user reaches that step. Executables with autorun = false are like before, only the last one of them will be considered and will be assigned to Click to Perform link. (Actually we may discuss keeping more than one executable, but if one of them is blocking the ui for user input we may have problems. For the autorun ones, I assume they are nonblocking.) If there are nothing but autorun executables, the hyperlink at the end of the step becomes Click to Complete.

Created an attachment (id=46406) Proposed patch
-my code between //ISAFER blocks -implementation not complete for executables in subitems and perform-when

One alternative to #1 would be to write a general purpose "composite command" whose sole purpose is to wrap and run several other commands in sequence with specific arguments.
About #2, it sounds like you're writing a fairly complicated cheat sheet, and that it's almost like you need to write a program that walks alongside the user as they are going through the cheat sheet. One question I would ask is why you couldn't do this work in the previous or next step's command? Do you have some kind of simple example that clearly demonstrates a need for this,to help me understand the motivation?

Yes, I am writing a big cheat sheet as part of my research. I am working on Mylar (http://www.eclipse.org/mylar/) and deriving Mylar tasks from cheat sheets. When a user comes to a specific step in the cheat sheet, I want to fire several Mylar commands at once (create a Mylar task, activate a Mylar task, organize and show/hide some views...) and I don't want the user know about the execution of these commands.

I can see the value in having a command or action which would be executed as soon as a step in a cheat sheet was entered and without having to press a button. For example if a cheat sheet uses a command to open a dialog which takes input which is stored in a cheat sheet variable, and that variable is used in a conditional-subitem you could do all of that in one step and save the user a key click.
I might go with a different syntax but I think that the idea is interesting. We need to consider what happens if the command fails.

Just out of curiosity, is there something wrong in using an attribute like "autorun" or is it because it's not very elegant.
About the failing commands, we may build a structure like try-catch. If a command fails then we can propose to execute another command (with a parameter of failing message or exception of the first command.) And if the second command fails too, we can just ignore.

bug.short_desc: registry does not save cache when parent configuration is read-only

long_desc.thetext:
If the parent configuration is read-only but the child configuration is read-write and both configurations do not contain registry cache files then the registry data is never cached on shutdown.
The issue seems to be in ExtensionRegistry.checkCache method. This method will look through the possible cache locations starting at the child location. - First it sets the file manager to the child configuration location. - If cache files are found in the child location then it continues to use the child file manager (in our case the files do not exist yet because we have never saved them yet). - If not then it moves to the read-only parent configuration and sets the file manager to the parent configuration location. - The extension registry will then continue to use the parent configuration file manager. - On shutdown the registry attempts to save the cache but the current configuration is read-only so it never saves the data (in ExtensionRegistry.stop()).
The registry should always save cache data to the child configuration but it this case it will only attempt to write to the read-only parent configuration.
The only way to work around this issue is to not use cascaded configurations by setting the property
osgi.configuration.cascaded=false

Please try with the recent 3.3 build and reopen if problem still exists.
(If I understand correctly the description, this was fixed in the bug 139690.)
There is a related issue that we don't split registry cache information between parent configuration and child configuration (it is either one or another). At present there is no plan to improve that aspect.
*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of 139690 ***
Oleg, how risky is this fix? Should we consider fixing this in 3.2.1?

The fix was pushed off from 3.2 to 3.3. The fix is simple, but touches a sensetive area.
Having in mind that this is the behavior registry had for a while, I would wait for a customer request before putting it into 3.2.1.
The workaround would be to run the eclipse once with "-initialize" from an account that has write priviledges on the parent location; it has been added into 3.2's readme in the bug 139972.

OK, when I ran into this issue while I was debugging a product which uses the -configuration option to point to a specific configuration directory. In this particular product the default configuration location (or parent) did not actually exist. In other words the base eclipse installation did not contain a configuration directory or a config.ini.
They instead only want to use the config.ini that is contained in their specified configuration location (from the -configuration option). In this particular scenario they really did not want to cascade their configurations so they really should be using the osgi.configuration.cascaded=false option anyway. Using the -initialize from a "root" user would not help them here.
So in this particular case I guess there is no real need to fix the bug in 3.2.1 because they should have been using the osgi.configuration.cascaded=false option anyway.

bug.short_desc: Trac repository connector should handle trailing slash

long_desc.thetext:
Track repository connector does not allow to have repository URl without trailing back slash.
PS: BTW, we need separate components in Bugzilla for Trac and Web repository connectors
I do not allow trailing slashes for Trac repository urls because a slash is appended by the connector when requests are made. Why do we need to support this?

(In reply to comment #1) > I do not allow trailing slashes for Trac repository urls because a slash is > appended by the connector when requests are made. Why do we need to support > this?
It is just beter user experience. You can cut that slash on save or do smarter concatenation if slash already there, so it would be transparent to the user.
Steffen: as Eugene indicates the user shouldn't have to care about the trailing slash, so just turn it into the form you're expecting if it is missing.

If I remove all trailing slashes before saving the task repository object this may be a bit odd because the user would expect to see exactly the entered url and not some normalized version.
If I allow trailing slashes and remove the slashes when connecting to the repository this may cause i ambiguity. Two repositories e.g http://trac.edgewall.org/ and http://trac.edgewall.org could be created which would both share the same task handles e.g. "http://trac.edgewall.org/ticket/1-1".
Mik, do you have any preference on how to solve this? How does Bugzilla handle this?

Allow the user to enter the trailing slash, but do not save it, e.g. by adding a stripTralingSlash(String) method. As you indicate we would never want two repositories of that kind. Put the code for stripping it into tasks.core, since this behavior should be generic.

This is guaranteed to cause users to think that the Trac connector isn't working (e.g. bug 151077), and while not critical would be best to fix for 0.6.1. If not fixed the FAQ entry needs to be updated: http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Mylar_FAQ#Trac_Connector_troubleshooting

(In reply to comment #6) > This is guaranteed to cause users to think that the Trac connector isn't > working (e.g. bug 151077), and while not critical would be best to fix for > 0.6.1.
Actually it should not be possible to create repositories with a trailing slash although this can be circumvented easily be adding a space. I'll look into getting this fixed as suggested in comment #5 today.

bug.short_desc: [Help] Generating a search index for a language before a local in that language generates errors in search results

long_desc.thetext:
Sometimes search results are displayed in pt language instead of the pt-BR locale that the browser is set to. Originally I had thought that this undesired behaviour was caused by plugin and fragment manifest missing the <?eclipse version="3.1" ?> tag under the document type definitions (See "Search results not displayed in correct locale" ), but it appears there is an alternate cause.
Constructing search indexes seem to be order dependant for languages supported at the language and locale level. For example:
.\jre\bin\java -DindexOutput=eclipse/plugins/com.ibm.db2.udb.doc_9.1.1000 -DindexLocale=pt_BR -jar eclipse/startup.jar -application org.eclipse.help.base.indexTool .\jre\bin\java -DindexOutput=eclipse/plugins/com.ibm.db2.udb.doc_9.1.1000 -DindexLocale=pt -jar eclipse/startup.jar -application org.eclipse.help.base.indexTool
produces the desired result for a pt-BR search (hits are listed in pt-BR when the topics are available in that local) while the following sequence of instructions causes pt text to be listed instead of pt-BR (the language the browser is set to) to be listed in the search results:
.\jre\bin\java -DindexOutput=eclipse/plugins/com.ibm.db2.udb.doc_9.1.1000 -DindexLocale=pt -jar eclipse/startup.jar -application org.eclipse.help.base.indexTool .\jre\bin\java -DindexOutput=eclipse/plugins/com.ibm.db2.udb.doc_9.1.1000 -DindexLocale=pt_BR -jar eclipse/startup.jar -application org.eclipse.help.base.indexTool
As a workaround for our SDF infocenter we can just index in the correct order, but we also ship our product for users to install in an InfoCenter scenario. We do not include pre-built search indexes for a couple reasons:
- the install image would be huge as our IC is supported in 28 languages - we will be using the updater which will make the pre-built search indexes invalid
Clients who have both Portuguese and Brazilian Portuguese users of their locally installed IC will be at risk of having a user search in Portuguese before Brazilian Portuguese, and thus generate search indexes that are incorrect.
I think the design should be changed. The language and the locale can be significantly different, and the language may not be comprehendable to the user of the locale. I am told that this is the case with Brazilian Portuguese being vastly different than Portuguese. Products, like ours, may have many more topics are translated into Brazilian Portuguese than Portuguese alone, so having just one index for the locale is a problem even if the user did understand the parent language as all the topics not translated in Portuguese would be listed in the search results in English.
If mulitple locales are to truely be supported by the help system, there needs to be distinct search indexes. The person administering the IEHS server can determine which indexes are created by listing the languages and locales in the start string so there is no need to have an additional (hidden) design constraint on which search indexes can be created.
